# 🔹 Topological Sort

Topological Sorting gives a **linear ordering** of vertices such that:

For every directed edge:

[
u \rightarrow v
]

Vertex **u appears before v**.

---

### Works Only On

✅ Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG)

---

### Algorithms

* Kahn's Algorithm (Queue + Indegree)
* DFS-based Topological Sort

---

### Complexity

[
O(V+E)
]

---

### Applications

* Course Scheduling
* Build Systems
* Task Scheduling
* Dependency Management

---

# 🔹 Dijkstra's Algorithm

### Purpose

Finds the **shortest path from a single source** to all other vertices.

---

### Works For

✅ Non-negative edge weights

❌ Does NOT work correctly with negative edge weights.

---

### Steps

1. Initialize distances.
2. Select the unvisited vertex with minimum distance.
3. Relax all adjacent edges.
4. Repeat.

---

### Example

```text
A --4--> B
|        |
2        5
|        |
C --1--> D
```

---

### Complexity

Using Binary Heap:

[
O((V+E)\log V)
]

Using Array:

[
O(V^2)
]

---

### Applications

* GPS Navigation
* Network Routing
* Robot Path Planning

---

# 🔹 Bellman-Ford Algorithm

### Purpose

Computes shortest paths from a single source.

### Special Feature

Works even if the graph contains **negative edge weights**.

---

### Algorithm

Relax every edge:

[
V-1
]

times.

Then perform one more iteration.

If any distance decreases again:

➡️ A **negative weight cycle** exists.

---

### Complexity

[
O(VE)
]

---

### Applications

* Currency Exchange
* Network Routing
* Negative Edge Detection

---

# 🔹 Dijkstra vs Bellman-Ford

| Feature               | Dijkstra       | Bellman-Ford |
| --------------------- | -------------- | ------------ |
| Negative Edges        | ❌ No           | ✅ Yes        |
| Detect Negative Cycle | ❌ No           | ✅ Yes        |
| Complexity            | O((V+E) log V) | O(VE)        |
| Faster                | ✅ Yes          | ❌ No         |

📌 Very common GATE comparison.

---

# 🔹 Relaxation

Relaxation means updating the shortest known distance.

If:

[
dist(u)+weight(u,v)<dist(v)
]

then update:

[
dist(v)
]

This is the core operation in both Dijkstra and Bellman-Ford.

---

# 🔹 Common GATE Traps

### Trap 1

BFS finds the shortest path **only in unweighted graphs**.

---

### Trap 2

Dijkstra fails for graphs with **negative edge weights**.

---

### Trap 3

Bellman-Ford detects **negative weight cycles**.

---

### Trap 4

Topological Sorting is possible **only for DAGs**.

---

### Trap 5

BFS uses a **Queue**.

DFS uses a **Stack**.

---

# 📝 Formula Sheet

| Algorithm        | Complexity     | Key Property               |
| ---------------- | -------------- | -------------------------- |
| BFS              | O(V+E)         | Shortest path (unweighted) |
| DFS              | O(V+E)         | Cycle detection            |
| Topological Sort | O(V+E)         | DAG only                   |
| Dijkstra         | O((V+E) log V) | No negative edges          |
| Bellman-Ford     | O(VE)          | Supports negative edges    |

